{
  "result": "Tonight the wind rattles the loose shutters of my imagination, coaxing me to remember the library where I once worked for a summer between oddly numbered years. Each evening, when the sun smeared orange fingerprints on the panes, the regulars arrived like characters in a novel shelving themselves. There was Mrs. Delaney, who always whispered hello to the biography of Eleanor Roosevelt before taking it home again, and a teenage saxophonist whose case smelled faintly of brass and rain.\n\nI sat behind the counter cataloguing donations, a slow meditation on the patience of paper. Some books arrived swollen with beach water, others crisp as fresh apples. About midway through July a man donated a box of astronomy journals from the nineteen seventies. They carried, between the equations and grainy photographs, the exhilaration of people first tasting the moon. Holding them, I realized how every piece of writing is a bottle tossed into time, trusting some future reader will uncork its message.\n\nWhen the heat finally broke, the townspeople brought baked goods for the staff. We ate lemon bars among the stacks, the tang of citrus mingling with glue and linen. Someone played a recording of cicadas on their phone, as though the season needed a soundtrack. The moment felt benign and miraculous, the way small things do when you understand their impermanence.\n\nNow, whenever the wind rattles, I think of that library breathing under the weight of voices, all of them waiting to be lifted again, remade through new eyes.",
